        <h3 class="article__heading">01. Challenge</h3>

        <p>Groups Recover Together is a healthcare organization that provides medication-assisted treatment for its 6,000+ members who are struggling with opioid addiction. Their comprehensive approach to addiction treatment combines medication, group counseling, and peer support to help members on their journey to recovery. They have 80+ treatment centers across the United States, as well as a telehealth offering that I designed <a class="anchor-body" href="/case-studies/groups" target="_blank">back in 2020</a> as a Product Design contractor at thoughtbot. I joined Groups' Product Team in April 2022 as a full-time Senior Product Designer.</p>

        <p>When I worked with Groups back in 2020, they had just transitioned over to a new EHR platform called eClincialWorks. While this platform helps their staff prescribe medication and coordinate care, it doesn't do a good job of organizing and presenting member information in a clear and intuitive way. It also doesn't have reporting, and cannot give insight about how a member is doing in general. Staff have to juggle multiple tabs and systems (e.g. Google sheets and Tableau reporting) in order to piece together a full picture of a member's journey and current state. This is inefficient and frustrating, and makes it difficult for staff to give members the most seamless care possible.</p>

        <h2 class="article__subheader">The Panel Summary Email</h2>

        <p>To bridge this gap, the Groups team created the Panel Summary, which contains a brief digest of a member's demographic, clinical, and medical history. It is sent in a daily email (like the <a class="anchor-body" href="/case-studies/groups-al" target="_blank">Action List</a>) to counselors and doctors, and gives an overview about each member they are going to see that day. The goal is to help them prepare for these encounters by summarizing a member's prescription details and recommendations, as well as their attendance and drug screen results for the last four weeks. This way, staff do not have to dig for this vital information about their member's care.</p>

