        <h3 class="article__heading">02. Process</h3>

        <h2 class="article__subheader">User Interviews</h2>

        <p>In order to get started, I scheduled interviews with various counselors and doctors to learn about their experience using the Panel Summary daily email. I asked them how it fits into their workflow ‚Äì how it helps them and how it hinders them. In these preliminary conversations I try to understand the bigger picture and the context in which a tool like this exists. I look for opportunities for improvement, as well things we should keep as we move forward with a new design. These conversations were super helpful in understanding what the next steps would be design-wise, and I came away with some key things to consider:</p>

         <div class="heading-lockup">
          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 1</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want to be able to see each others' Panel Summaries to make last minute coverage easier to orchestrate</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 2</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want the Panel Summary to better capture nuanced data. For example, they want to know if they should be worried about an illicit screen, or whether a member attended a makeup group session</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 3</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want a deeper dive into a member's attendance history, looking back to eight weeks instead of four. This will give them a better idea if a member is at risk for discharge due to poor attendance</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 4</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want a richer medical and clinical history about a member. They want to see more details about their prescriptions, as well as any underlying problems or diagnoses they might have</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 5</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want flags and alerts to highlight important things, like when a member missed a drug screen or if their prescription is about to expire</h4>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="article__subheader">Design</h2>

        <p>After I had enough clarity on the context of the Panel Summary and how it's used by counselors and doctors, I was ready to design what it could look like out of email and into our Digital Platform. When starting a brand new redesign like this, the first thing I do is gather inspiration from competitors and creative platforms like Dribbbl and Pinterest. In this case, I looked for UI examples of EHRs, CRMs, healthcare apps, complex tables, and dashboards.</p>

        <p>After additional rounds of feedback sessions with stakeholders, I landed on an interface that's rich with information yet easy to parse. It took many iterations to get the visual design, organization, and hierarchy right. I use bar charts, alerts, and collapsible panels to help staff focus on what's important to them. I use colors and font styles consistently and selectively, to convey meaning and a sense of priority. I wanted the visual design to be invisible, pleasing, and predictable; to minimize distraction and let the data speak for itself. Ultimately, I wanted a staff member to read a member's Panel Summary and know exactly what they need to do to keep that member engaged and in treatment.</p>

